R Markdown Introduction

This is an R Markdown document. The code chunk knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE) is used to setup the document and how it processes these chunks below. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You need to label your code chunks, and these labels must be unique. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

2. With the data(cars) dataset in R, compute the following:

  1. the median of the stopping distance
data(cars)
median(cars$dist)

  1. the mean of the speed
mean(cars$speed)
## [1] 15.4
  1. the six number summary of both the stopping distance and speed
summary(cars)

plot(dist~speed, data = cars, xlab = "speed", ylab = "distance",main = "Speed and Stopping Distance of Cars")

3. With the data(iris) dataset in R, do the following calculations:

  1. the sum of the 25th and 26th versicolor iris’s sepal lengths divided by 2
data(iris)
sum(iris$Sepal.Length[25] + iris$Sepal.Length[26])/2
## [1] 4.9
  1. the sum of all petal lengths among all species of iris that are between 0 cm and 3 cm
sum(iris$Petal.Length[iris$Petal.Length<3])
## [1] 73.1
  1. assuming x equals the sepal length of the 10th virginica iris, then \(4\cdot x/2^3\)
4*iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species=="virginica"][10]/(2^3)
## [1] 3.6
  1. assuming x equals the sum of all setosa sepal widths, then \(4\cdot(x/2)^3\).
4*(sum(iris$Sepal.Width[iris$Species == "setosa"])/2)^3
## [1] 2517691

4. Using the Instructor Notes from Week 03, address the following:

  1. run the code that appears in slide 20 of the intro_slides.pdf slide deck.
set.seed(13) ## set the random seed
x <- rnorm(n = 20) ## generate predictor variable
y <- rnorm(n = 20, mean = x) ## generate response variable
plot(y ~ x, pch = 19) ## plot (x,y) pairs

  1. change the seed number in the set.seed() command from 13 to 14. Then, re-run the code in part a.
set.seed(14)
x <- rnorm(n = 20) ## generate predictor variable
y <- rnorm(n = 20, mean = x) ## generate response variable
plot(y ~ x, pch = 19) ## plot (x,y) pairs

  1. Is there a difference between the results of parts a and b? If so, describe some of the obvious differences.

Yes there are different points that are generated from the random distribution, which results in a different plot.

  1. Why is it important to set the random seed at the beginning of a simulation?

So that our results are consistent; otherwise the data will always be different and the simulation will give different results every time.
